o one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Isabel Vermandois was born about 1460, in Oise, Picardie, France. She had at least 1 daughter with Earl Robert Corbet de Beaumont-le-Roger, Earl of Licester,Comte Muelan. She died on 13 February 1531, in Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 72."},"et":{"Abt. 1460–13 Feb 1531":"umbes 1460–13. veebruar 1531","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1480–1505":"1480–1505","1460–1531":"1460–1531","1510":"1510","1531":"1531","Aft. 1505":"pärast 1505","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","Abt. 1460":"umbes 1460","1505":"1505","13 Feb 1531":"13. veebruar 1531","Sens, Saone-et-Loire, Bourgogne, or St.Nicaise, Meulan, Yvelines, Ile-de